British newspapers, covering a recent three year period. A second important source of information is a quantitative survey for which a representative sample of 2000 UK residents was questioned. These sources are supplemented by the study of contemporary books and film material, as well as medieval chronicles for comparative purposes, and the author also draws on cultural theory to highlight the characteristics and functions of distant memory and myth. The investigation culminates in considering the potential impact of memory of the Norman Conquest in Britain today. Siobhan Brownlie is a Lecturer in the School of Arts, Languages & Cultures at the University of Manchester.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective memoryzGreat Britain. 0aNormansxPublic opinion. 0aNormanszGreat BritainxHistoriography. 0aPublic opinionzGreat Britain. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAttitudes.  aBeliefs.  aContemporary British Memory.  aDistant Memory.  aImpact.  aMyth.  aNewspaper Articles.  aNorman Conquest.  aQuantitative Survey.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204162740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782041627423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782041627/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles